SYSTEM-COMMANDS:
----------------
>sudo passwd			#To set the root user a password.
>sudo su			#To login as the root user.
>sudo -h				#Help parameters for sudo 
>sudo apt-get udpate -y			#Download and install latest security patches.
>sudo apt-get upgrade			#Download and install latest OS upgrade.
>sudo apt-get install <pckg-name>	#Download any package(software)
Eg: apt-get install htop
>apt-get remove <package-name>	#To remove a particular package.
Eg:apt-get remove htop
>apt-get purge <package-name>	#To completely remove all the packages installed on your system.
>apt-get autoremove		#To remove all the unnecessary packages automatically.
>service --status-all		#To list the services launched at start-up.
>sudo service <name> stop	#To stop a runnig service
>sudo apt-get remove <name>	#To remove a service.

>dpkg --list		#To list all the packages installed on your system.
>info			#Similar to man, but often provides more detailed or precise information.
>uname -a 		#Provides wide range basic info about the system.
>top			#Displays the process using the most resources.
>man 			#Displays manual page
>man man		#Provides info about the manual itself
>man intro		#Provides brief intro on linux commands
>whatis <command>	#provides info on what the command does.
Eg: whatis mkdir

Memory::
--------
>free			#Displays the free memory on the system.
>free -m		#To list the memory in the system.
>vmstat			#provides info on the virtual memory
>sudo lshw -c memory	#To list the RAM type and speed.
>df			#Displays filesystem
>df -h			#To list the filesystems and volumes
>du			#Directory usage.Displays the size of the direcories.
















